def to_timeseries(df, tcol, freq="5min"):
    # Set timestamp as index
    if tcol is not None and tcol in df.columns:
        df = df.set_index(pd.to_datetime(df[tcol], errors="coerce"))
        df = df.drop(columns=[tcol])
    else:
        df.index = pd.to_datetime(df.index, errors="coerce")

    # Drop rows where timestamp parsing failed
    df = df[~df.index.isna()].sort_index()

    # 🔹 Keep only numeric columns for resampling
    numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include="number")

    # Resample and interpolate
    numeric_df = numeric_df.resample(freq).mean()
    return numeric_df.interpolate(method="time").ffill().bfill()

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.ensemble import IsolationForest
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

# ---------------------------
# Utility Functions
# ---------------------------

def find_time_col(df):
    """Find the most likely timestamp column"""
    for c in df.columns:
        try:
            pd.to_datetime(df[c])
            return c
        except Exception:
            continue
    return None

def to_timeseries(df, tcol, freq="5min"):
    """Convert dataframe to time-series with only numeric columns"""
    # Use timestamp as index
    if tcol is not None and tcol in df.columns:
        df = df.set_index(pd.to_datetime(df[tcol], errors="coerce"))
        df = df.drop(columns=[tcol])
    else:
        df.index = pd.to_datetime(df.index, errors="coerce")

    # Drop invalid timestamps
    df = df[~df.index.isna()].sort_index()

    # 🔹 Keep only numeric sensor columns
    numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include="number")

    # Resample and interpolate
    numeric_df = numeric_df.resample(freq).mean()
    return numeric_df.interpolate(method="time").ffill().bfill()

def detect_anomalies(df, contamination=0.05):
    """Apply IsolationForest anomaly detection"""
    model = IsolationForest(contamination=contamination, random_state=42)
    preds = model.fit_predict(df)
    scores = -model.decision_function(df)  # anomaly score (higher = more anomalous)

    df["anomaly"] = (preds == -1).astype(int)
    df["anomaly_score"] = scores
    return df, model

def fuse_probabilities(df, cols):
    """Fuse multiple sensor anomaly scores into a single probability"""
    scaler = MinMaxScaler()
    probs = scaler.fit_transform(df[cols])
    df["fused_prob"] = probs.mean(axis=1)  # simple average fusion
    return df

def plot_results(df, sensor_cols):
    """Plot sensor values + anomaly markers"""
    for col in sensor_cols:
        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
        plt.plot(df.index, df[col], label=col)
        plt.scatter(df.index[df["anomaly"] == 1],
                    df[col][df["anomaly"] == 1],
                    color="red", label="Anomaly", marker="x")
        plt.title(f"{col} with Anomalies")
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()

# ---------------------------
# Main Script
# ---------------------------

# Load datasets (replace with your actual paths)
seer_path = r"D:\Downloads\seer_fish_data.csv"
tuna_path = r"D:\Downloads\tuna_fish_data.csv"

for path in [seer_path, tuna_path]:
    print(f"\nProcessing {path} ...")

    # Load raw
    df_raw = pd.read_csv(path)

    # Find timestamp column
    tcol = find_time_col(df_raw)

    # Convert to timeseries
    ts = to_timeseries(df_raw, tcol=tcol)

    # Select numeric sensor columns
    sensor_cols = [c for c in ts.columns if pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(ts[c])]

    # Detect anomalies
    ts, model = detect_anomalies(ts[sensor_cols])

    # Fuse anomaly scores
    ts = fuse_probabilities(ts, ["anomaly_score"])

    # Show a preview
    print(ts.head())

    # Plot results
    plot_results(ts, sensor_cols)
